Date: Wed, 12 Nov 1997 10:32:36 -0600
From: Tario <Tario@mcn.net
At this late date I cannot cite the reference but it appeared in the USA
medical [literature during the 1940's. The case cited was that of an
engineer who was inspecting a Texas cave to appraise the possibility of a
guano mining operation for use as fertilizer. Several of the large caves in
Texas have bat colonies numbering in the millions. The engineer was
definitely not bitten by a bat but did contract rabies which proved fatal.
It was mentioned that he had a "lesion" on his neck prior to entering the
cave but otherwise nothing unusual was noted. It was conjectured at that
time that the infection came from aerosolized bat urine.
Robert J. Hosley
e-mail: Tario@mcn.net

