Date: Wed, 12 Nov 1997 10:23:50 -0700
From: "Charles H. Calisher" <calisher@usa.healthnet.org
I am always amazed that certain basic studies have not been done with
important infectious disease agents, including rabies. I received a message
from someone at CDC/Atlanta telling me that studies of the infectivity of
bat urine have not been done.
What is needed is a logical, organized, and thorough study of bat urine,
saliva, feces, etc. I don't even know whether bats urinate WHILE they
are flying. Anyway, the work is not being done. I suggest that someone
with appropriate facilities and experience submit a grant proposal to
obtain funding for such a study.
--
Charles H. Calisher, Ph.D.
Moderator, ProMED-mail
Colorado State University
Fort Collins, Colorado, USA
[The above communications indicate that this is an area of current
ignorance and due for scientific clarification, if only to reduce public
over-reaction to bat populations. - Martin Hugh-Jones, ProMED-AHEAD
